Comments one <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Taiwanese</ENAMEX> businessman , " You worry that your kid is going to become a communist . "
<ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Taiwanese</ENAMEX> people in the mainland invariably wish to maintain their ties with <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Taiwan</ENAMEX> , and are particularly anxious to ensure that their children can integrate quickly into the school system back home once they return .
With the number of <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Taiwanese</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Dongguan</ENAMEX> increasing in <ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">recent years</ENAMEX> , it was just a matter of time before a <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Taiwanese</ENAMEX> school was established .
Thanks to the vigorous advocacy of <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">H. D. Ye</ENAMEX> , the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG">TBAD</ENAMEX> began working seriously in <ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">1994</ENAMEX> to establish a school , but the difficulties were considerable .
They had to find land , funds , teachers , and much more .
With <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Taiwanese</ENAMEX> and mainland authorities at political loggerheads , the school 's promoters had to jump through hoops every step of the way in seeking to hire teachers from <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Taiwan</ENAMEX> , use <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Taiwanese</ENAMEX> teaching materials , and appoint a <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Taiwanese</ENAMEX> person to the post of principal .
